&gt; Keys help React identify which items have changed, are added, or are
&gt; removed.

 Keys should be given to the elements inside the array to give them a **stable identity**, and they only make sense in the context of the surrounding array, so it doesn&#39;t matter if two isolated lists have elements with equal keys as long as they are not equal inside the same list (repeated ids). There is no problem with the following code

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    {
        arr.map((item,index) =&gt;{
            //defining key only once per `arr` iteration
            const key = uniqueId(index)
            return(
                &lt;div key={key}&gt;
                     {
                        arr2.map((item, index) =&gt; &lt;span key={key} /&gt;)
                     }
                &lt;/div&gt;
            )
        })
    }

Note that the key is only relevant within a particular parent React element. React won’t try to “match up” elements with the same keys between different parents. (React doesn’t have idiomatic support for moving a host instance between different parents without re-creating it.) [Font][1]

See the [docs here][2]


  [1]: https://overreacted.io/react-as-a-ui-runtime/
  [2]: https://reactjs.org/docs/lists-and-keys.html

